3.6

a)

Explain why this is a resonable prior for theta_i.

Its a resonable prior because of how we interpret the parameters of a beta distribution prior, which is that alpha is the number of prior successes and beta is the number of prior failures. We have prior information in the form of the overall freethrow percentages of each player, but we need to turn that into a number of successes and failures. We dont know and cant really guess those values since they depend on the number of attempts of each player. To solve this, we make a simplification that each player had the same number of prior attempts and model it as exp(m) where m is normal random variable; because of the exponent, each players overall freethrow proportion gets multiplied by some number to convert it to prior successes and failures, and we estimate the value of m from the data.

b)

Explain the role of m in the prior.

The role of m is to allow the overall free-throw percentage of each player to be turned into a prior number of successes and failures, which is how we interpret the alpha and beta parameters of the beta distribution. Since we dont know and cant guess the overall number of freethrow attempts for each player, an easy way is to assume that they all had the same number of attempts, exp(m), and estimate the value of m from the data. It has to be a positive number, so we exponentiate a normal random variable and give it a very uninformative prior.

d)

Write you own MCMC algorithm to compute a table of posterior means and 95% credible intervals for all 11 model parameters.

Since the theta-is have conjugate beta priors, but m has a non-conjugate Normal prior, it would be best to use the Gibbs-within-Metropolis sampling method.

Define the sampler parameters and initial values

S <- 200000
samples <- matrix(NA, S, 11)
prop <- rep(0, S)
#Inits
#Use 0.1 as initial value for all thetas -- want to make sure that we don't bias the chains at all.
theta <- rep(0.1, 10)
#0 corresponds to a single prior observation for the beta prior
m = 0
can_sd <- 1.2

Note: the standard deviation for the candidate distribution was tuned during several burn-in runs of 20000 so that the acceptance probability is about 0.4. Thus, this represents a final run with that tuning parameter set to a fixed value.

Make a log posterior function for the sampler

log_post_m <- function(theta, m, q) {
  #Likelihood is the sum of the i beta priors with log parameterization
  lik <- sum(dbeta(theta, shape1=(exp(m)*q), shape2=(exp(m)*(1-q)), log = TRUE))
  #Prior for m is N(0, 10)
  prior <- dnorm(m, mean=0, sd=sqrt(10), log=TRUE)
  #Posterior is log(lik) + log(prior)
  post <- lik + prior
  return(post)
}

Make the Metropolis-Gibbs sampler

for (s in 1:S) {
  
  ############################
  ###Metropolis sampling for m
  ############################
  #Candidate value for m randomly drawn from N(previous m, candidate_sd)
  can <- rnorm(1, mean=m, sd=can_sd)
  #Calculate the acceptance ratio as the difference in the log posterior of the candidate m minus the current m
  logR <- log_post_m(theta, can, players$overall) - log_post_m(theta, m, players$overall)
  #If statement to accept with prob min(1, R)
  if (log(runif(1)) < logR) {
    #If accepted, assign candidate as new value for m
    m <- can
  }
  #Ifelse statement that saves a value of 1 if the candidate is accepted and 0 if not
  #This is used for tuning the can_sd parameter
  prop.out <- ifelse(log(runif(1)) < logR, 1, 0)
  
  ##########################
  #Gibbs sampling for thetas
  ##########################
  #Loop through each of the 10 theta parameters and sample from the full conditional posterior derived in the hand-written notes
  for (i in 1:N) {
    theta[i] <- rbeta(1, shape1=(players[i, 2] + exp(m)*players[i, 1]), shape2 = (players[i, 3] - players[i, 2] + exp(m)*(1 - players[i, 1])))
  }
  
  #Save the samples
  samples[s,] <- c(theta, m)
  #Save the acceptance indicator
  prop[s] <- prop.out
}

#Calculate the acceptance proportion
mean(prop)
## [1] 0.427475

For the theta parameters, the results were generally pretty similar with the custom algorithm giving much smaller intervals that for the most part were entirely contained within the JAGS intervals. The biggest difference between the methods is seen in the estimation of the m parameter. JAGS gives a much smaller estimate (0.66) compared to the custom algorithm (5.63); these correspond to about 1.94 and 279 prior attempts, respectively. Intuitively, it seems like the custom algorithm gives a better answer here since 279 seems like a more reasonable value than 1.94 for prior number of freethrow attempts. On the other hand, the 95% credible interval for m is much larger for the custom algorithm compared to JAGS, so it seems to imply more uncertainty about our estimate for this parameter.

Given that the chains seem to be mixing well for both methods here, it seems odd that they give such different values. At first I thought it was a coding error on my part, but I couldnt find anything wrong with the custom algorithm. Im still not sure why they give such different answers.

f)

The advantages of the JAGS method is that there is much less work up front specifying the model because you dont need to derive full conditional distributions or come up with a function to compute the log posterior. Other advantages include the fact that you dont need to code the sampling algorithm, you can run multiple chains simultaneously, there is seemingly automatic adjustment of tuning parameters, and there are built-in functions to summarize the draws and quickly make trace plots. The biggest disadvantage is that you dont really know whats going on under the hood in the sampling from the posterior, so you have less understanding of the functions and distributions underlying the sampling.

The main advantage of the custom algorithm is that by making it, you learn a lot about the math behind the scenes since you have to think about whether you priors are conjugate or not, and whether to use Gibbs or Metropolis sampling or both. You also have a lot more control over the fine details, like the candidate distribution and the tuning parameters. The disadvantages include the time and effort to code it, the fact that it can only run one chain at a time (but this can easily be changed), and the slow speed that it runs at.

#First, transform the standard t-distribution function with some help from Wikipedia
dt_ls <- function(y, df, mu, sigma) {
  return(1/sigma * dt((y - mu)/sigma, df))
}
